document.title: K-12 Science Literacy New Hampshire Curriculum Framework

B471EEC0DFE601316A4668A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some jobs/careers require knowledge and use of physical science content and/or skills.

B4713E30DFE601316A4468A86D17958E.description: Provide examples of items that are manufactured or produced.

B470F1F0DFE601316A4368A86D17958E.description: Provide examples of how man uses energy in everyday life, such as providing light, warmth in winter, cooling in summer, TVs, computers, telephones, transportation, factories.

B470A640DFE601316A4268A86D17958E.description: Social Issues (Local and Global) Energy, Power, and Transportation Manufacturing

B4705770DFE601316A4168A86D17958E.description: Demonstrate how to use tools, such as rulers, scales, balances, magnifiers and thermometers to measure properties of objects, such as size, weight, temperature.

B46FF630DFE601316A4068A86D17958E.description: Identify tools and simple machines, such as a wheel, and explain how they work.

B46F31B0DFE601316A3E68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that new objects can be made out of physical materials, such as cloth and paper.

B46E94B0DFE601316A3C68A86D17958E.description: The growth of scientific knowledge in Physical Science has been advanced through the development of technology and is used (alone or in combination with other sciences) to identify, understand and solve local and global issues.

B46E4160DFE601316A3B68A86D17958E.description: Describe the position of an object by referencing its location in relation to another object or background.

B46DCA20DFE601316A3A68A86D17958E.description: Describe and demonstrate how the position and motion of an object can be changed by applying force, such as pushing and pulling; and explain that the greater the force, the greater the change.

B46D6330DFE601316A3968A86D17958E.description: Describe the many different ways things can move, such as in a straight line, zigzag or circular motion, back and forth, and fast and slow.

B46CCA50DFE601316A3768A86D17958E.description: Describe and demonstrate that things close to the Earth drop to the ground unless something supports them.

B46C7E90DFE601316A3668A86D17958E.description: Describe the properties of magnetism and demonstrate how magnets can be used to move some things without touching them.

B46BD530DFE601316A3468A86D17958E.description: The motion of an object is affected by force.

B46B80F0DFE601316A3368A86D17958E.description: Recognize that energy comes from different sources, such as electricity and water, and is utilized in many common objects.

B46B0610DFE601316A3268A86D17958E.description: Describe that heat can be produced in a variety of ways, such as burning, rubbing, and mixing substances together.

B46AACF0DFE601316A3168A86D17958E.description: Explain that the Sun provides the Earth with heat and light.

B46A4650DFE601316A3068A86D17958E.description: Recognize that sound is produced by vibrating objects and that the pitch of the sound can be varied by changing the rate of vibration.

B469A700DFE601316A2E68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that not all materials react the same way when an action is applied to them.

B4695C30DFE601316A2D68A86D17958E.description: Describe how the properties of certain materials can change when specific actions are applied to them, such as freezing, mixing, heating, cutting, dissolving and bending.

B468C3C0DFE601316A2B68A86D17958E.description: Energy is necessary for change to occur in matter. Energy can be stored, transferred and transformed, but cannot be destroyed.

B4686960DFE601316A2A68A86D17958E.description: Identify the observable properties of different objects, such as color, size, shape, weight and texture.

B467B380DFE601316A2868A86D17958E.description: Recognize that objects can be made of one or more materials.

B4676870DFE601316A2768A86D17958E.description: Recognize that objects can be composed of different types of materials, such as wood, metal, and paper.

B466CDE0DFE601316A2568A86D17958E.description: All living and nonliving things are composed of matter having characteristic properties that distinguish one substance from another (independent of size/amount of substance).

B4662A30DFE601316A2368A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some jobs/careers require knowledge and use of life science content and/or skills.

B4658FD0DFE601316A2168A86D17958E.description: Provide examples from personal experience that illustrate how medicine helps humans recover from illness.

B4653E90DFE601316A2068A86D17958E.description: Recognize that technology is used in medicine to prevent and cure diseases through vaccinations and medications.

B464E880DFE601316A1F68A86D17958E.description: Social Issues (Local And Global) Medical Technology and Biotechnology

B4649600DFE601316A1E68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some tools, such as magnifiers, balances and thermometers, have special uses and can help gather information and extend the senses.

B463FCB0DFE601316A1C68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that new products can be made out of natural materials, such as paper from trees and cloth from various plants and animals.

B4635010DFE601316A1A68A86D17958E.description: The growth of scientific knowledge in Life Science has been advanced through the development of technology and is used (alone or in combination with other sciences) to identify, understand and solve local and global issues.

B462EE50DFE601316A1968A86D17958E.description: Recognize that humans need food, water, air, waste removal and a particular range of temperatures in their environment, just as other animals do.

B46284A0DFE601316A1868A86D17958E.description: Recognize and describe the human life cycle from birth to old age.

B46231B0DFE601316A1768A86D17958E.description: Recognize that two parents, both a father and mother, are required for human reproduction.

B461D1D0DFE601316A1668A86D17958E.description: Identify the sense organs, including eyes, ears, nose mouth, and skin; and describe how each can warn an individual about danger.

B46185C0DFE601316A1568A86D17958E.description: Recognize similarities and individual differences among people, and that children closely resemble their parents.

B460DEF0DFE601316A1368A86D17958E.description: Recognize symptoms, such as fever, rashes, coughing and congestion for common illnesses.

B4609130DFE601316A1268A86D17958E.description: Identify and describe the basic personal hygiene habits for maintaining good health, such as washing one's hands with soap and water and brushing one's teeth.

B4603F00DFE601316A1168A86D17958E.description: Recognize that humans can spread germs that cause disease.

B45FE630DFE601316A1068A86D17958E.description: Recognize that proper nutrition, exercise and rest are all important factors in maintaining good health.

B45F3F80DFE601316A0E68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some of the things humans can do, such as playing games, reading, and writing, must be learned.

B45EF4D0DFE601316A0D68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that humans can gather different kinds of information about an object by adjusting their proximity to it.

B45EA990DFE601316A0C68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that humans learn from each other in many different ways, such as listening and speaking, watching and imitating.

B45E53B0DFE601316A0B68A86D17958E.description: Recognize and describe how living things respond when exposed to helpful and harmful situations.

B45D9DF0DFE601316A0968A86D17958E.description: Humans are similar to other species in many ways, and yet are unique among Earth's life forms.

B45ACBB0DFE601316A0168A86D17958E.description: Recognize that there are different species of living things in various places around the world.

B45A80F0DFE601316A0068A86D17958E.description: Recognize and describe the similarities and differences in both behavior and appearance of plants and animals.

B459E3D0DFE6013169FE68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some plants and animals, which are alive today, are similar to living things which have become extinct, such as elephants and mammoths.

B4593100DFE6013169FC68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some living things, which lived on Earth long ago, are now extinct, such as dinosaurs, mammoths, giant tree ferns, and horsetail trees.

B4587C10DFE6013169FA68A86D17958E.description: Groups of organisms show evidence of change over time (e.g. evolution, natural selection, structures, behaviors, and biochemistry).

B45D3CB0DFE601316A0868A86D17958E.description: Identify the resources plants and animals need for growth and energy, and describe how their habitat provides these basic needs.

B45C75D0DFE601316A0668A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some plants and animals go through changes in appearance when the seasons change.

B45C1710DFE601316A0568A86D17958E.description: Recognize that animals, including humans, interact with their surroundings using their senses; and that different senses provide different kinds of information.

B45BC670DFE601316A0468A86D17958E.description: Recognize that living things can be found almost anyplace in the world; and that specific types of environments are required to support the many different species of plant and animal life.

B45B1890DFE601316A0268A86D17958E.description: Energy flows and matter recycles through an ecosystem.

B4581D70DFE6013169F968A86D17958E.description: Recognize that living things have a life cycle, during which they are born, grow, and die.

B457B420DFE6013169F868A86D17958E.description: Recognize that parents and offspring of many species closely resemble one another; and describe the similarities in appearance of given plant and animal families.

B456FFC0DFE6013169F668A86D17958E.description: Recognize that plants and animals have features that help them survive in different environments.

B4563520DFE6013169F468A86D17958E.description: Recognize plants and animals as living things and describe how they are alike and different.

B455D860DFE6013169F368A86D17958E.description: Differentiate between living and nonliving things; and categorize objects in each group using the significant observable characteristics they share, such as color, shape and size.

B4554180DFE6013169F168A86D17958E.description: All living organisms have identifiable structures and characteristics that allow for survival (organisms, populations, and species).

B454A200DFE6013169EF68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some jobs/careers require knowledge and use of Earth science content and/or skills.

B453F480DFE6013169ED68A86D17958E.description: Describe actions that can help the environment, such as recycling and proper disposal of waste materials.

B4539AB0DFE6013169EC68A86D17958E.description: Identify environments that are natural, such as a forest, meadow, or mountains and those that have been built or modified by people, including cities, roads, farms, and houses.

B4534190DFE6013169EB68A86D17958E.description: Differentiate between natural and man-made materials.

B4529610DFE6013169E968A86D17958E.description: Recognize, and with assistance, safely demonstrate the use of tools to gather data and extend the senses, such as thermometers, hand lenses and balances.

B451FFF0DFE6013169E768A86D17958E.description: The growth of scientific knowledge in Earth Space Science has been advanced through the development of technology and is used (alone or in combination with other sciences) to identify, understand and solve local and global issues.

B451B260DFE6013169E668A86D17958E.description: Recognize there are too many stars to count, and that they are unequal in their brightness.

B45102C0DFE6013169E468A86D17958E.description: The origin and evolution of galaxies and the universe demonstrate fundamental principles of physical science across vast distances and time.

B450A1E0DFE6013169E368A86D17958E.description: Explain that people should not look directly at the Sun because it is dangerous and may cause injury to the eyes.

B4505840DFE6013169E268A86D17958E.description: Recognize that as the position of the Sun changes in relation to the Earth it creates shadows of varying length and direction.

B4500DB0DFE6013169E168A86D17958E.description: Recognize that the Sun, Moon and stars all appear to move slowly across the sky.

B44F76E0DFE6013169DF68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that the light and heat the Sun provides to the Earth is necessary for life.

B44EC320DFE6013169DD68A86D17958E.description: Recognize the basic patterns of the Moon, including its appearance sometimes at night and sometimes during the day; and how it appears to change shape through the month.

B44E6B10DFE6013169DC68A86D17958E.description: Recognize the basic patterns of the Sun, including its appearance during the daytime, and how its position in the sky changes through the seasons.

B44DCE50DFE6013169DA68A86D17958E.description: The Earth is part of a solar system, made up of distinct parts, which have temporal and spatial interrelationships.

B44D8150DFE6013169D968A86D17958E.description: Recognize that water can be a liquid or a solid; and explain that it can be made to change from one state to the other, but the amount (mass) of water always remains the same in either state.

B44CD9E0DFE6013169D768A86D17958E.description: Describe rocks and soils in terms of their physical properties.

B44C8980DFE6013169D668A86D17958E.description: Explain that large rocks can be broken down into smaller rocks.

B44BE7C0DFE6013169D468A86D17958E.description: Recognize that some changes are too slow or too fast to be easily observed.

B44B28B0DFE6013169D268A86D17958E.description: Recognize that Earth materials have a variety of properties, including size, shape, color and texture.

B44ACA30DFE6013169D168A86D17958E.description: Use observable properties, such as color and texture, to classify and organize rocks and minerals.

B44A7E40DFE6013169D068A86D17958E.description: Recognize that solid rocks, soils, and water in its liquid and solid states can be found on the Earth's surface.

B449D760DFE6013169CE68A86D17958E.description: Describe and compare weather using observations and measurements of local weather conditions.

B44980A0DFE6013169CD68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that weather conditions change frequently, and that weather patterns change over the seasons.

B448E550DFE6013169CB68A86D17958E.description: The Earth and Earth materials, as we know them today, have developed over long periods of time, through constant change processes.

B44845A0DFE6013169C968A86D17958E.description: Collaborate, as a group, with another classroom or school.

B44799E0DFE6013169C768A86D17958E.description: Take part in sharing information with another classroom or school as a group.

B446E210DFE6013169C568A86D17958E.description: Keep a visual or written journal.

B4463490DFE6013169C368A86D17958E.description: Plan and carry out simple activities with a group.

B44576B0DFE6013169C168A86D17958E.description: Use computer software and various technologies as appropriate to display and communicate information and ideas.

B444CE70DFE6013169BF68A86D17958E.description: Look for evidence to support ideas.

B4447900DFE6013169BE68A86D17958E.description: Compile observations (one to one relationship) by making or using simple pictographs, tally charts or simple graphs.

B4442740DFE6013169BD68A86D17958E.description: Ask questions and take part in investigations.

B4438930DFE6013169BB68A86D17958E.description: Make a graph to represent data.

B4433060DFE6013169BA68A86D17958E.description: Use pictures or other means to organize ideas.

B442E4F0DFE6013169B968A86D17958E.description: Make observations and tell ideas about real-life issues.

B4423E50DFE6013169B768A86D17958E.description: Communicate ideas and observations through a variety of tools and formats (e.g., oral, journal, drawing, projects, multimedia).

B4418230DFE6013169B568A86D17958E.description: Use age-appropriate sources such as newspapers, books and websites.

B440DFB0DFE6013169B368A86D17958E.description: Have experience with a variety of media sources.

B4403590DFE6013169B168A86D17958E.description: Science Skills for Information, Communication and Media Literacy
comments: (from ICT Literacy Map for Science, www.21stcenturyskills.org)

B43FE770DFE6013169B068A86D17958E.description: Provide examples of how people throughout history have used legends and stories to explain how the world works.

B43F9B50DFE6013169AF68A86D17958E.description: Describe how most things are made up of multiple parts and explain that things may not work if some parts are missing.

B43F45A0DFE6013169AE68A86D17958E.description: Identify multiple ways to solve a design problem.

B43EF9D0DFE6013169AD68A86D17958E.description: Provide examples that highlight the importance of the planning phase of any project.

B43EAC30DFE6013169AC68A86D17958E.description: Demonstrate that all tools have a special purpose (e.g., to measure, to help in observations, to make things or to make things better).

B43E61C0DFE6013169AB68A86D17958E.description: Science and Technology, Technological Design and Application

B43E1500DFE6013169AA68A86D17958E.description: Use observation skills to describe the area around their homes and school.

B43DC370DFE6013169A968A86D17958E.description: Common Environmental Issues, Natural Resources Management and Conservation

B43D7230DFE6013169A868A86D17958E.description: Ask questions of others about their work.

B43CBCF0DFE6013169A668A86D17958E.description: Work with a partner to accomplish a specific task.

B43BBC80DFE6013169A368A86D17958E.description: Draw an object and the object in use.

B43B6380DFE6013169A268A86D17958E.description: Identify shape and use of objects.

B43AA190DFE6013169A068A86D17958E.description: Observe that things can change in different ways, such as in size, weight, color and movement.

B43A3550DFE60131699F68A86D17958E.description: Understand that people can keep track of some things by seeing where they come from and where they go.

B439D100DFE60131699E68A86D17958E.description: Discover that things change in some ways and stay the same in some ways.

B4393890DFE60131699C68A86D17958E.description: Provide examples to explain that things in nature and things people make have very different sizes, weights, ages and speeds.

B438EB70DFE60131699B68A86D17958E.description: Explain how one way to describe something is to say how it is like something else.

B4389840DFE60131699A68A86D17958E.description: Describe how a model of something is different from the real thing but can be used to learn something about the real thing.

B437D970DFE60131699868A86D17958E.description: Explain that something may not work if some of its parts are missing.

B4377970DFE60131699768A86D17958E.description: Observe that when parts are put together, they can do things that they couldn't do by themselves.

B43728B0DFE60131699668A86D17958E.description: Show how most things are made of parts.

B4368560DFE60131699468A86D17958E.description: Explain that sometimes people aren't sure what will happen because they don't know all the factors that may have an effect on the outcome.

B43636D0DFE60131699368A86D17958E.description: Discover that when a scientific investigation is done the way it was done before, we expect to get a very similar result.

B435E9D0DFE60131699268A86D17958E.description: Recognize that information can be obtained merely by careful observation, but sometimes even more data can be collected by conducting scientific investigations.

B434F200DFE60131698F68A86D17958E.description: Identify and describe patterns and relationships in observed objects and events.

B4348FC0DFE60131698E68A86D17958E.description: Represent and interpret information and observations in many ways (such as in tally, pictographs, bar graphs, tables).

B43447F0DFE60131698D68A86D17958E.description: Representing and Understanding Results of Investigations

B433B6D0DFE60131698B68A86D17958E.description: Follow their own plan for conducting an investigation.

B4332030DFE60131698968A86D17958E.description: Predict how changing one part of an exploration will affect the outcome.

B432BC40DFE60131698868A86D17958E.description: Suggest a plan and describe a sequence of events for conducting an exploration.

B4326CB0DFE60131698768A86D17958E.description: Select tools and procedures, in a purposeful way, to explore objects and materials.

B431DC40DFE60131698568A86D17958E.description: Sort and classify object materials and events based on one or more attributes; and explain the methods used for sorting.

B4319280DFE60131698468A86D17958E.description: Ask questions that lead to exploration and investigation as a result of working with materials and objects.

B4314210DFE60131698368A86D17958E.description: Ask questions about objects, organisms and events in their immediate environment.

B430EB50DFE60131698268A86D17958E.description: Record observations using language, concrete objects, and symbolic representations.

B4309AE0DFE60131698168A86D17958E.description: Make observations and explore materials using all of their senses (one sense at a time).

B42FEF60DFE60131697F68A86D17958E.description: Scientific Inquiry and Critical Thinking Skills (INQ)
